subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis. Males of
G. foxi
resemble those of
G. heleios
,
G. iviei
,
G . caaguara
,
G . januari
and
G . camisea
by the presence of anterior tooth ( Figs. 90A, C ). They are distinguished from the latter species by the widely excavated conductor lamina in dorsal view ( Figs. 91C , 92H ). Females resemble those of
G. heleios
and
G. hirsutissima
by having a basal constriction on the spermathecae ( Fig. 92D ). They are differentiated from the latter species by the presence of a well-developed CFO ( Fig. 90E ).
Description. Male and female described by Levi (1980) . Additional data.

Male ( USA , Pennsylvania , AMNH )
. Habitus as in Figures 89A–D . Total length 1.47. Cephalothorax 0 60 long, 0.42 wide, 0.57 high. Abdomen 0.82 long, 0.75 wide, 0.72 high. Sternum 0.32 long, 0.35 wide. Eye diameters and interdistances: AME 0.05, ALE 0.05, PME 0.06, PLE 0.04. AME-AME 0.05, AME-ALE 0.07, PME-PME 0.06, PME-PLE 0.08, ALE-PLE 0.01. Clypeus height 2.00. Three promarginal and four retromarginal teeth ( Figs. 90A– C ). Anterior tooth present ( Figs. 90A, C ). Leg measurements: I: femur 0.82 + patella 0.25 + tibia 0.75 + metatarsus 0.62 + tarsus 0.40, total 2.85; II: 0.70, 0.22, 0.65, 0.45, 0.30, 2.32; III: 0.45, 0.17, 0.32, 0.35, 0.27, 1.57; IV: 0.72, 1.50, 0.50, 0.45, 0.27, 3.45. Femur III and IV without trichobothria. DTS 0.06. DTE 0.37. Palp as in Figures 91E– H . Embolus tip widened ( Figs. 91D , 92G ). Conductor retrolateral apophysis rounded ( Figs. 91B–C ). Conductor lamina widely excavated in dorsal view ( Figs. 91C , 92H ).

caption.paragraph:
FIGURE 89.
Glenognatha foxi
from USA (AMNH). A–D, male habitus. A, dorsal. B, lateral. C, ventral. D, frontal. E–H, female habitus. E, dorsal. F, lateral. G, ventral. H, frontal. Scale bars, 200 µm.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Female ( USA , Arizona , AMNH )
. Habitus as in Figures 89E–H . Total length 1.75. Cephalothorax 0.70 long, 0.55 wide, 0.55 high. Abdomen 1.00 long, 0.97 wide, 1.02 high. Sternum 0.35 long, 0.42 wide. Eye diameters and interdistances: AME 0.05, ALE 0.03, PME 0.05, PLE 0.03. AME-AME 0.06, AME-ALE 0.05, PME-PME 0.07, PME-PLE 0.07, ALE-PLE 0.01. Clypeus height 1.70. Three promarginal and four retromarginal teeth ( Figs. 90D– F ). Cheliceral fang outgrowth well-developed ( Fig. 90E ). Leg measurements: I: femur 0.67, patella 0.22, tibia 0.60, metatarsus 0.52, tarsus 0.35, total 2.37; II: 0.62, 0.21, 0.50, 0.45, 0.35, 2.13; III: 0.45, 0.12, 0.27, 0.30, 0.22, 1.37; IV: 0.67, 0.17, 0.45, 0.42, 0.36, 2.08. Femur III and IV without trichobothria. DTS 0.08. DTE 0.37. Tracheal system as in Figures 92J–L . Spermathecae with a basal constriction ( Fig. 92D ). UE entire ( Figs. 92A–C ).

caption.paragraph:
FIGURE 90.
Glenognatha foxi
from USA (AMNH). A–C, male left chelicerae. A, anterior. B, posterior. C, mesal. D–F, female left chelicerae. D, anterior. E, posterior. F, mesal. Scale bars, 100 µm. AT: anterior tooth. Prt: promarginal tooth. CFO: cheliceral fang outgrowth. Ret: retromarginal tooth.

subSubSection.paragraph: Variation. Male total length 1.2–1.8 ( N = 10; average 1.6), cephalothorax length 0.6–0.8 ( N = 10; average 0.7), femur I length 0.7–1.0 ( N = 10; average 0.8). Female total length 1.4–1.8 ( N = 10; average 1.6), cephalothorax length 0.6–0.7 ( N = 10; average 0.69), femur I length 0.6–0.8 ( N = 10; average 0.6).

Distribution. Known from southern Canada to
Panama
( Fig. 134 ).

FIGURE 91.
Glenognatha foxi
from USA (AMNH). A–D, male left palp, schematic. A, ventral. B, conductor, ventral. C, conductor, dorsal (arrow, excavation). D, embolus, ventral. E–H, male left palp. E, ventral. F, dorsal. G, prolateral. H, retrolateral. Scale bars, 100 µm. C: conductor. CB: cymbium. CRa: conductor retrolateral apophysis. E: embolus. ED: ejaculatory duct. EMg: embolic medial groove. P: paracymbium. T: tegulum. TO: tarsal organ.
